</form><html xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:math="java.lang.Math" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:fo="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Format" xmlns:fn="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-functions" xmlns:xdt="http://www.w3.org/2005/02/xpath-datatypes" xmlns:caml="http://lc.ca.gov/legalservices/schemas/caml.1#" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><head><title>AB2487:v98#DOCUMENT</title><meta name="dc:identifier" content="AB2487"/><meta name="dc:title" content="AB &#xA;              2487-&#xA;                AMENDED&#xA;              "/><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;charset=utf-8"/></head><body><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Start</h2></span><div id="bill_all" align="justify"><div id="about"><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td align="center"><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Amended
               IN </span><span style=" text-transform: uppercase; font-size: 1em">
                Assembly
              </span> <span style="text-transform: uppercase">March 19, 2026</span><br/></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td align="center"/></tr></tbody></table></div><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><font size="3" style="FONT-FAMILY: MinionPC, Arial Unicode MS">
                    CALIFORNIA LEGISLATURE—
                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 2487</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member<font color="#B30000"><strike> Macedo</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i> Ahrens</i></font><br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>February 20, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"><font color="#B30000"><strike>An act to amend Section 96114 of the Government Code, relating to academic volunteers. </strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>An act to add Chapter 13 (commencing with Section 11910) to Part 1 of Division 3 of Title 2 of the Government Code, relating to artificial intelligence.</i></font></span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 2487, as amended, <font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:Legislator><caml:Name>Macedo</caml:Name></caml:Legislator></strike></font>&nbsp;<font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Ahrens.
                          </i></font><font color="#B30000"><strike>California Academic Volunteer and Mentor Service Act of 1992. </strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Artificial intelligence: education and workforce development.</i></font></span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the California Community Colleges, under the administration of the Board of Governors of the California Community Colleges, as one segment of public postsecondary education in the state. Existing law establishes community college districts throughout the state, and authorizes them to provide instruction at the campuses they operate and maintain. Existing law establishes the California Online Community College, under the administration of the board of governors, for specified purposes, and requires the college to develop a Research and Development Unit to, among other things, focus on using technology, data science, behavioral science, machine learning, and artificial intelligence to build out student supports.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would enact the
			 Artificial Intelligence Education and Workforce Development Act to accomplish specified goals, including, among others, empowering and supporting community college instructors in using and deploying artificial intelligence (AI) responsibly in administrative and classroom settings, and strengthening the state’s AI and technology workforce pipeline by upskilling and educating all workers so they can benefit from AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the California Community Colleges, upon appropriation by the Legislature, to, among other things, develop and disseminate to community college districts statewide guidance on the use of AI in community colleges, explore, facilitate, and support specified partnerships to develop and implement AI literacy and skills development initiatives, support the integration of AI literacy into the preparation and ongoing professional development of community college instructors, and establish a pilot program encouraging integration and adoption
			 of AI tools in community college classrooms, as specified. The bill would also require the California Community Colleges, upon appropriation by the Legislature, to submit a report to the Legislature based on findings provided by a working group convened by the California Community Colleges for this purpose that includes, among other things, a summary of barriers to support community college districts in providing and deploying cloud-based AI services into administrative or educational settings in community colleges, as specified.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the Governor’s Office of Business and Economic Development, also known as “GO-Biz,” to, among other duties, serve the Governor as the lead entity for economic strategy and the marketing of California on issues relating to business development, private sector investment, and economic growth. Existing law establishes the Office of Small Business Advocate within GO-Biz to advocate for causes of small business and to
			 provide small businesses with the information they need to survive in the marketplace.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the Office of Small Business Advocate, upon appropriation by the Legislature, to establish and maintain for small businesses educational resources and modules containing information on specified topics related to AI, as provided. The bill would require the office, within one year following funding, to prepare and submit a progress report to the Legislature and other appropriate state officials and agencies summarizing its efforts in developing and publishing the educational resources and modules. The bill would require the office to convene an AI advisory group, with a prescribed membership, and consult with other state agencies and individuals, as specified, regarding the educational resources and modules.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require GO-Biz, upon appropriation by the Legislature, and in close partnership with the
			 California Community Colleges, to support training, reskilling, and upskilling initiatives for workers using AI or supporting the AI industry in order to bolster state economic competitiveness and maximize opportunities for the labor force. The bill would require GO-Biz, on or before January 1, 2029, and every 2 years thereafter, to submit a report to the Legislature and other appropriate state officials and agencies summarizing its efforts on the initiatives.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would also require GO-Biz, upon appropriation by the Legislature, to establish local AI training hubs, including physical or virtual centers that provide education and hands-on training in AI development and application for the purpose of building a skilled local workforce, as provided. The bill would require GO-Biz, upon appropriation by the Legislature and in coordination with other state agencies, to convene a working group to administer a statewide program to develop the skilled workforce to
			 support infrastructure and energy requirements of the AI industry, as provided. The bill would authorize funding to be awarded through a competitive application process to local workforce development boards and other specified entities to deliver education and hands-on experience in AI data center operations, energy infrastructure, and other sectors, as provided. The bill would also require GO-Biz to undertake other specified duties related to workforce development.</div></i></font><font color="#B30000"><strike><p style="display:inline;"><s>The California Academic Volunteer and Mentor Service Act of 1992 creates the Academic Volunteer and Mentor Service Program, administered by the office of the Governor, in order to provide academic support and guidance to each child who requires it, as provided. The act sets forth the intent of the Legislature that funding for purposes of the act be appropriated in the annual Budget Act, as provided.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>This bill would make a nonsubstantive change to the latter provision.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></strike></font></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase"><font color="#B30000"><strike>NO</strike></font><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>YES</i></font></span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.16401688049051988"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;"><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>SECTION 1.</i></font></h3> <font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i>Chapter 13 (commencing with Section 11910) is added to Part 1 of Division 3 of Title 2 of the Government Code, to read:</i></font></div><div><font color="blue" class="blue_text"><i><div><div id="id_D8EBD4E0-23CF-40B5-87B6-E8B2651FB9D6"><div><h5 style="text-align:left;">
                CHAPTER
               13. Artificial Intelligence Education and Workforce Development Act</h5></div></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11910.</h6> This chapter shall be known, and may be cited, as the Artificial Intelligence Education and Workforce Development Act.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11911.</h6> (a) The Legislature finds and declares all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Artificial intelligence (AI) will have profound impacts on the economy, national security, education, and the future of work.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Equipping community college students, instructors, and workers with AI literacy and related skills is essential for the United States’ and the state’s workforce competitiveness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Innovation and competitiveness in the age of AI requires a robust workforce, including workers trained in AI development, deployment, data labeling, and cybersecurity, and supporting infrastructure in energy, broadband, and high-performance
						  computing.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) The state must invest in future-ready pathways, including strengthened mathematics and science competency and career education and career technical education aligned to emerging technologies, with supporting coursework and resources.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Community colleges must adopt AI safely and equitably, with a commitment to protecting data privacy, promoting transparency, avoiding algorithmic discrimination, and ensuring that instructors and students are empowered and supported.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Instructors must lead AI integration. Instruction is most powerful when instructors have the training, time, and tools to deploy AI safely, responsibly, and confidently, beginning with administrative tasks and progressing to instructional uses as instructors determine appropriate.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(7) AI, when implemented safely and responsibly, is a powerful tool for equity to ensure that every student can access the best instruction, regardless of their background, language, or disability. AI-powered supports remove barriers for historically underserved students.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(8) States have begun issuing guidance for responsible AI integration in community colleges.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(9) AI literacy requires modern infrastructure, including statewide broadband, modern classroom devices, secure networks, open educational resources, research capacity, privacy protections, and procurement systems that allow responsible innovation.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The purpose of this act is to accomplish all of the following goals:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Empowering and supporting community college instructors in
						  using and deploying AI responsibly in administrative and classroom settings.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Preparing community college students for an AI-enabled world, and harnessing its beneficial uses.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Ensuring safe, ethical, privacy-preserving AI deployment in community college education.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Modernizing learning, promoting equitable access to AI tools, and supporting technology and its benefits.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Supporting lifelong learning and skilling initiatives that support the state’s economic competitiveness and labor force in the age of AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) Strengthening the state’s AI and technology workforce pipeline by upskilling and educating all workers so they can benefit from
						  AI.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11912.</h6> For purposes of this chapter, the following definitions apply:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(a) “Artificial intelligence” or “AI” means an engineered or machine-based system that varies in its level of autonomy and that can, for explicit or implicit objectives, infer from the input it receives how to generate outputs that can influence physical or virtual environments.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) “CalOSBA” means the California Office of Small Business Advocate created by subdivision (b) of Section 12098 within the Governor’s Office of Business and Economic Development established in Section 12096.2.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) “Data labeling” means the process of annotating datasets to enable machine learning
						  models to identify and classify information.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) “GO-Biz” means the Governor’s Office of Business and Economic Development established in Section 12096.2.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) “STEM” means science, technology, engineering, and mathematics.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11913.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall develop and disseminate statewide guidance to community college districts on the use of AI in community colleges.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The guidance in subdivision (a) shall focus on all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Providing community college instructors and staff with the training, time, and tools to guide the use of AI within community college education safely and responsibly.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Harnessing the productivity benefits of AI for instructors and administrators, and prioritizing reduction of administrative burdens.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Complying with relevant rules and compliance requirements that address ethical and appropriate use in community college education, and the best uses of AI given current capabilities and features in the job market, focusing on reducing uncertainties and helping community colleges comply with state requirements.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Promoting an understanding of generative AI and its implications across academic subjects.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) The California Community Colleges, to the extent possible and where appropriate, shall seek to align the guidance in subdivision (a) with existing frameworks, research, and guidance, including that of other states.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11914.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall fund, within existing resources, the development of model curriculum on AI for use in community colleges.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall, within existing resources, collaborate with community college instructors to develop, and regularly update as appropriate, educational resources on AI in community colleges. These resources may reflect technological changes or pedagogical research.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) The California Community Colleges shall post on its internet website the model curriculum and educational
						  resources developed pursuant to subdivisions (a) and (b).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) The California Community Colleges shall consider mechanisms to make educational resources developed pursuant to subdivision (b) more accessible statewide at minimal cost to community college districts, which may include requiring these resources to be placed in the public domain or released under an open license that permits no-cost access, use, adaptation, and redistribution by others with no or limited restrictions.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) The California Community Colleges shall broadly encourage local adoption and awareness of the model curriculum and educational resources developed pursuant to subdivisions (a) and (b) by community college districts, and shall encourage local adoption into new or existing educational programs.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11915.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall explore, facilitate, and support partnerships between community college districts, career education and career technical education training providers, local workforce development boards, employers across technology and nontechnology sectors, and nonprofit and community-based organizations to develop and implement AI literacy and skills development initiatives.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Initiatives supported under subdivision (a) shall, to the extent practicable, be aligned with regional and statewide workforce needs, and may include, but are not limited to, all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Codesign
						  of AI-related curriculum and work-based learning opportunities that prepare community college students for in-demand occupations.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Integration of AI tools into career education, career technical education, apprenticeships, and upskilling programs for incumbent workers.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Collaboration with small and medium-sized businesses, industry associations, and chambers of commerce to identify priority use cases and skill gaps.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Initiatives described in subdivision (a) shall include both of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Reviewing successful AI literacy, education, and workforce training approaches from other states and countries, including public and private partnership models.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Supporting the launch
						  of pilot programs consistent with this chapter to test, refine, and evaluate AI education and workforce training models.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) AI providers and other participating employers in initiatives provided under this section are encouraged to provide reduced-cost or subsidized access to AI tools, instructional materials, and technical assistance to community college instructors, community college districts, and workforce training providers to enable research, testing, and program development.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11916.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall support the integration of AI literacy into the preparation and ongoing professional development of community college instructors.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The support provided under subdivision (a) shall include, but is not limited to, practical guidance on all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Identifying administrative tasks that are appropriate and inappropriate for automation or AI deployment.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Identifying educational tasks that are appropriate or inappropriate uses of AI for pedagogical purposes, including ethics and safety
						  considerations, and opportunities for using AI to enhance community college instruction, curriculum, and courses.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Monitoring student use to ensure safety and positive educational outcomes.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) The California Community Colleges shall encourage community college districts to allocate dedicated time for community college instructors to learn about AI, redesign their lesson plans, participate in peer learning, and attend structured AI training.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) The California Community Colleges may partner with labor organizations, technology providers, and other entities where appropriate to support the integration of AI literacy into the professional development of community college instructors, including, but not limited to, workshops and summer institutes.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) The California Community Colleges may, within existing resources, make grants available to community college districts to support the integration of AI literacy into community college instructor professional development activities, consistent with existing programs where possible, and issuing clarifying guidance on use of grant funds where appropriate.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11917.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall convene a working group to study and submit a report to the California Community Colleges that includes, but is not limited to, all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) A summary of the procedural, procurement, and technical barriers to support community college districts in responsibly providing and deploying cloud-based AI services into administrative or educational settings in community colleges.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Legislative or administrative recommendations to overcome the barriers provided in paragraph (1).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;"> (3) Review and
						  analysis of all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Community college district budgeting templates and procurement guidelines.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Opportunities or barriers to statewide procurement of AI tools or services led by the California Community Colleges, rather than individual community college districts.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Legislative, regulatory, or administrative changes that would better support and encourage responsible and effective adoption of AI literacy and AI tools in community colleges statewide.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Existing broadband infrastructure and community college information technology capacity, and whether they are sufficient to support equitable access to AI-enabled learning, and how resources or policy changes would help fill this gap.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) (1) On or before January 1, 2029, the California Community Colleges shall submit a report to the Legislature based on the findings provided by the working group pursuant to subdivision (a).</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) A report submitted to the Legislature pursuant to this subdivision shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11918.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, the California Community Colleges shall establish a pilot program that encourages deeper integration and adoption of AI tools in community college classrooms than is otherwise common across the state, and that integrates a research team to study its overall impact on learning outcomes and classroom efficiency to guide further deployments.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) In designing and operating the pilot program in subdivision (a), the California Community Colleges shall consider all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Consent and willing participation from community college instructors and community college students.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Ensuring studies are consistent with research ethics and best practices.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Scalability of the pilot program’s design statewide.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) (1) On or before January 1, 2029, and every two years thereafter, the California Community Colleges shall submit a report to the Legislature and other appropriate state officials and agencies summarizing its efforts on the initiatives described in this section. The California Community Colleges shall also post the report on its internet website.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) A report submitted to the Legislature pursuant to this subdivision shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11919.</h6> (a) The Legislature finds and declares that AI tools can support small businesses to become more productive and efficient and to compete in a global marketplace.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b)  The purpose of this section is to assist small business concerns in evaluating and adopting AI models or tools productively and responsibly in business operations.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, CalOSBA shall establish and maintain educational resources and modules for small businesses and make those educational resources and modules publicly available on a new or existing online learning platform or internet website.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) The educational resources and modules developed under this section shall, to the extent practicable and appropriate, provide information on all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) How AI models and tools work, including the limits of the capabilities of those models.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) How to identify the best uses of AI, including examples of the types of tasks and functions that AI can reliably and effectively perform for small businesses, including how AI may improve operations, productivity, or customer service.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) How to remain updated on the emergence, development, and technological maturation of AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) How to understand and evaluate the policies, terms, and conditions applicable to users of AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) The best practices in selecting and partnering with third-party providers of AI tools.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(6) How to effectively identify, evaluate, and manage the risks of AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(7) Responsible use of AI in a business context, including how to ensure the privacy of user or customer inputs to AI tools.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(8) How to retain human involvement in important decisions informed by recommendations made by AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) In developing and publishing the educational resources and modules described in this section, CalOSBA shall do all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Ensure that the information contained in the educational resources and modules is factually accurate and current.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Ensure that the educational resources and modules are useful and actionable, and presented in a manner that is easily comprehensible by small business concerns.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Consider and incorporate relevant existing information and resources developed by other entities, including private entities, as appropriate.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Consider strategies and activities to encourage the discoverability, awareness, impact, and adoption of the educational resources and modules during development and publication.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(5) Avoid giving preference to any particular AI model, tool, or service provider.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(f) (1) Within one year following funding of this section, CalOSBA shall prepare and submit a progress
						  report to the Legislature and other appropriate state officials and agencies summarizing its efforts in developing and publishing the educational resources and modules described in this section. CalOSBA shall also post the report on its internet website.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) A report submitted to the Legislature pursuant to this subdivision shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(g) (1) CalOSBA shall convene an AI advisory group that CalOSBA may consult with on an ongoing basis regarding the information contained in the educational resources and modules established under this section. The advisory group shall be composed of the following members, who shall be selected by CalOSBA:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Individuals with demonstrated expertise in AI, including not less than one individual from each of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(i) The private sector.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(ii) Academia.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 4em;">(iii) An organization with demonstrated expertise in evaluating the quality of AI outputs, including quality, reliability, or security.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) One or more individuals with demonstrated expertise in the creation of educational or professional development materials regarding AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) One or more individuals with demonstrated expertise in outreach to small business concerns.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) CalOSBA shall consult with other state agencies, as appropriate, and with other researchers, subject matter experts, and industry partners, as appropriate or needed, regarding the educational resources and modules
						  developed under this section.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11920.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, GO-Biz, in close partnership with the California Community Colleges, shall support training, reskilling, and upskilling initiatives for workers using AI or supporting the AI industry in order to bolster state economic competitiveness and maximize opportunities for the labor force.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) The initiatives to be considered include, but are not limited to, all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Training programs or online courses offered by vocational schools, community colleges, and other institutions in machine learning, data annotation, AI operations, cybersecurity, and human-centered AI design.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Certificate and credential programs for AI support roles.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Community college bootcamps, or new credential tracks, aligned to employer demand.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) (1) On or before January 1, 2029, and every two years thereafter, GO-Biz shall submit a report to the Legislature and other appropriate state officials and agencies summarizing its efforts on the initiatives described in this section. GO-Biz shall also post the report on its internet website.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) A report submitted to the Legislature pursuant to this subdivision shall be submitted in compliance with Section 9795.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11921.</h6> (a) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, GO-Biz shall establish local AI training hubs, including physical or virtual centers that provide education and hands-on training in AI development and application for the purpose of building a skilled local workforce.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Hubs shall do all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Provide access to graphics processing unit-equipped computing environments and AI tools for training purposes.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Partner with cloud service providers and local employers.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Enable access to AI education and training.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Support job placement in local and national industries.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Hubs may be colocated at local workforce development board locations, community colleges, or regional data center campuses.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11922.</h6> (a) The purpose of this section is to develop a skilled workforce capable of constructing, operating, and maintaining the physical and energy infrastructure necessary to support AI innovation across sectors. This includes data and computing centers, high-performance computing clusters, broadband systems, energy grids, and climate-resilient AI facilities.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, GO-Biz, in coordination with other relevant state agencies, including the California Community Colleges, shall convene a working group to administer a statewide program to develop the skilled workforce to support infrastructure and energy requirements of the AI industry.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) The program described in subdivision (b) shall establish and fund education and training programs that do both of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Prepare workers for high-demand technical careers in the construction and maintenance of AI and energy infrastructure.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Align with industry-recognized credentials and labor standards, including registered apprenticeships.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(d) Funding may be awarded through a competitive application process to local workforce development boards, community college districts, unions, and technical training providers to deliver education and hands-on experience, which may include, but is not limited to, any of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) AI data center operations and construction, which may include any of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Site preparation, heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC), liquid cooling, and smart facility integration.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Network wiring, server assembly, and rack configuration.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Data center safety, emissions monitoring, and energy management.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Energy infrastructure, which may include any of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Grid scale and microgrid electrical systems for computer environments.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Diverse and scalable energy mix for AI campuses.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Load balancing, grid interconnection, and net zero design.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Broadband and digital infrastructure, which may include any of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Fiber splicing, trenching, and last mile broadband for edge AI.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Low latency networking for AI training environments.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Secure communications and sensor installation for energy AI coordination.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Resilient construction and sustainability, which may include any of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Energy efficient building design and construction, low carbon materials, and water efficiency.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Heat reuse systems and AI-aware building management.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Permitting, compliance,
						  and other program management functions.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(e) In administering the program, GO-Biz shall seek to do all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) Partner with employers and unions to offer industry-led apprenticeships and on-the-job training.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) Develop bridge programs for dislocated workers transitioning from fossil fuel, manufacturing, or logistics industries.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) Prioritize program delivery in high unemployment, rural, or energy transition regions.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(4) Support matriculation between community college programs and credentialed workforce pathways.</div></p></div><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">11923.</h6> Upon appropriation by the Legislature for this express purpose, GO-Biz shall do all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(a) Align workforce development investments with state infrastructure planning and permitting, broadband deployment, and energy or climate planning.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) Create a statewide registry of AI infrastructure training programs and workforce needs by region.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(c) Partner with stakeholders, including regional data center operators, utilities, and energy developers, to forecast long-term hiring demand and skills requirements.</div></p></div></div></i></font></div></div><font color="#B30000"><strike><caml:BillSection id="id_448BC657-81A6-496A-ADF1-24BA894D90C3"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>SECTION 1.</caml:Num><caml:ActionLine action="IS_AMENDED" xlink:href="urn:caml:codes:GOV:caml#xpointer(%2Fcaml%3ALawDoc%2Fcaml%3ACode%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'TITLE'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'15.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'CHAPTER'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'3.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawHeading%5B%40type%3D'ARTICLE'%20and%20caml%3ANum%3D'6.'%5D%2Fcaml%3ALawSection%5Bcaml%3ANum%3D'96114.'%5D)" xlink:label="fractionType: LAW_SECTION" xlink:type="locator">Section 96114 of the <caml:DocName>Government Code</caml:DocName> is amended to read:</caml:ActionLine><caml:Fragment><caml:LawSection id="id_8EDFB1C6-DC81-43B8-9457-517B710DF457"><div style="margin:0 0 0.5em 0;"></div><caml:Num>96114.</caml:Num><caml:LawSectionVersion id="id_5D612864-D684-404B-A9DF-CC1C3B9AC811"><caml:Content><p style="display:inline;"><s>(a)<span class="EnSpace"/>It is the intent of the Legislature that funding for purposes of this chapter be appropriated in the annual Budget Act.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div><p style="display:inline;"><s>(b)<span class="EnSpace"/>Of any amount appropriated for the purposes of this chapter for any fiscal year, an amount not exceeding 5 percent may be applied to the administrative expenses of the office of the Governor with regard to this chapter. To the extent that the amount made available pursuant to this subdivision is not sufficient to meet those administrative expenses, the responsibilities of the office of the Governor under this chapter shall be performed, to the
				  extent feasible, with funding from other available sources.</s></p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"></div></caml:Content></caml:LawSectionVersion></caml:LawSection></caml:Fragment></caml:BillSection></strike></font></div></div></body></html>
